1
00:00:00,012 --> 00:00:02,030
Previusly on Kyle XY...

2
00:00:02,159 --> 00:00:03,007
What is it?

3
00:00:04,145 --> 00:00:08,081
It's you. 1985?

4
00:00:08,157 --> 00:00:10,733
I found out his name--the guy in the photo.

5
00:00:10,733 --> 00:00:11,897
Adam Bailen.

6
00:00:11,931 --> 00:00:15,101
Adam Bailen has been missing for 20 years.

7
00:00:15,184 --> 00:00:16,893
You got to stop asking questions.

8
00:00:16,893 --> 00:00:21,248
Forget about the past, because if you don't, they'll kill you, Kyle.

9
00:00:21,801 --> 00:00:25,831
781227 was scheduled for termination two months ago.

10
00:00:26,297 --> 00:00:30,340
This company cannot afford to have that subject loose in the outside world.

11
00:00:30,411 --> 00:00:31,282
Kyle!

12
00:00:31,616 --> 00:00:33,133
It's all gonna be okay.

13
00:00:34,938 --> 00:00:37,741
I've got a great thing going with her,
and I'm not gonna ruin it.

14
00:00:37,758 --> 00:00:41,180
Great for you.
Go out with Amanda, tap Hillary on the side.

15
00:00:41,516 --> 00:00:44,582
I can't help feeling that I've let you down.

16
00:00:44,796 --> 00:00:45,961
Let me down?

17
00:00:46,385 --> 00:00:48,900
You made me feel like I was your son.

18
00:00:49,356 --> 00:00:51,270
Noah, is that really you?

19
00:00:52,858 --> 00:00:54,212
Who are you?

20
00:00:55,245 --> 00:00:56,531
It's Mom.

21
00:00:57,067 --> 00:00:59,001
We finally found you.

22
00:01:01,866 --> 00:01:04,141
The kids called us...

23
00:01:06,307 --> 00:01:07,652
It's gonna be okay.

24
00:01:07,805 --> 00:01:09,422
We'll figure this out.

25
00:01:09,505 --> 00:01:10,701
That's about what happened.

26
00:01:11,325 --> 00:01:14,221
As you can imagine, so do we.
It's all we've been talking about...

27
00:01:14,406 --> 00:01:17,901
<i>At a glance, anyone would believe the Petersons and I were related.</i>

28
00:01:18,246 --> 00:01:20,950
<i>They'd say I had her mouth and his chin.</i>

29
00:01:21,307 --> 00:01:24,053
<i>But I wanted more than a passing resemblance.</i>

30
00:01:24,255 --> 00:01:28,603
<i>Instead of thinking they could be my parents, I needed to feel that they were.</i>

31
00:01:28,796 --> 00:01:30,530
They look like nice people.

32
00:01:31,327 --> 00:01:33,291
What the hell kind of name is Noah?

33
00:01:33,527 --> 00:01:34,593
I can't believe you.

34
00:01:34,657 --> 00:01:38,003
Kyle's about to get hauled off by his parents. Can't you think of something decent to say?

35
00:01:38,126 --> 00:01:39,862
It's not like I want him to go.

36
00:01:39,875 --> 00:01:41,771
He doesn't even look like a Noah.

37
00:01:42,798 --> 00:01:45,462
Do you think they'll want to take me home with them soon?

38
00:01:46,177 --> 00:01:47,291
Maybe.

39
00:01:49,526 --> 00:01:50,782
I don't know.

40
00:01:51,028 --> 00:01:53,612
Well, we'd been living in Hong Kong for two years when it happened.

41
00:01:53,617 --> 00:01:56,032
Five years ago Noah left for school, 
never came home.

42
00:01:56,405 --> 00:02:00,391
We thought it was a kidnapping,
some sort of extortion scheme.

43
00:02:00,886 --> 00:02:03,010
David's an executive for a bank.

44
00:02:03,028 --> 00:02:04,793
But there was never any ransom call.

45
00:02:04,806 --> 00:02:06,982
I mean there were no clues at all right from the beginning.

46
00:02:06,996 --> 00:02:11,912
And still...we never stopped looking for him,
never stopped hoping.

47
00:02:12,735 --> 00:02:18,450
And finally, out of nowhere,
a hit on a missing person web site.

48
00:02:18,456 --> 00:02:23,930
We couldn't tell from the picture, but after talking to the detective and now seeing him.

49
00:02:26,096 --> 00:02:29,002
I used to call him my wandering wonder--

50
00:02:29,497 --> 00:02:34,873
Sharp, inquisitive, studying everything,
taking it all in.

51
00:02:36,248 --> 00:02:40,711
Kyle is--I'm sorry. 
We're so used to calling him that.

52
00:02:40,717 --> 00:02:41,760
I understand.

53
00:02:42,248 --> 00:02:46,992
Kyle is special and different in many ways.

54
00:02:47,037 --> 00:02:50,623
He was born with some physical defects.

55
00:02:50,718 --> 00:02:52,762
His organs weren't all in the right place.

56
00:02:52,765 --> 00:02:56,991
But the corrective surgeries have made him as good as new, but without a belly button.

57
00:02:59,025 --> 00:03:00,903
We have so many questions.

58
00:03:01,677 --> 00:03:02,800
So do we.

59
00:03:02,806 --> 00:03:03,933
Well, they'll have to wait.

60
00:03:04,006 --> 00:03:07,032
The hospital arranged some DNA tests to verify paternity.

61
00:03:07,138 --> 00:03:08,411
In the meantime...

62
00:03:08,575 --> 00:03:13,743
We were told that Noah has no memory from the day before he was found.

63
00:03:13,888 --> 00:03:15,812
I put this photo album together.

64
00:03:15,945 --> 00:03:17,810
Thought it might jog some memories.

65
00:03:36,295 --> 00:03:38,171
You said you had answers.

66
00:03:47,945 --> 00:03:50,670
Foss, listen to me. I know you're there.

67
00:03:52,727 --> 00:03:54,551
Who are these people?

68
00:04:21,665 --> 00:04:23,081
I have questions.

69
00:04:24,166 --> 00:04:25,241
Go ahead.

70
00:04:25,385 --> 00:04:26,581
Where am I from?

71
00:04:27,458 --> 00:04:28,771
Well, let's see.

72
00:04:28,976 --> 00:04:33,513
You were born in Manhattan,
and from there we moved around a little bit--

73
00:04:33,988 --> 00:04:36,730
D.C., Connecticut, Hong Kong.

74
00:04:36,736 --> 00:04:39,412
-Do I have any brothers or sisters?
-We only wanted one child.

75
00:04:39,475 --> 00:04:41,650
-Pets?
-We're both allergic.

76
00:04:41,708 --> 00:04:43,741
Kyle, slow down.

77
00:04:43,788 --> 00:04:46,162
Maybe if we tell you some stories.

78
00:04:47,665 --> 00:04:52,093
You remember the old claw-foot tub,
from the house in Connecticut?

79
00:04:52,497 --> 00:04:56,083
When we were moving to Hong Kong,
Noah kept insisting he didn't want to go

80
00:04:56,086 --> 00:04:58,553
because he didn't know what the tub would be like.

81
00:04:58,757 --> 00:05:02,121
David, as a surprise, had the tub shipped.

82
00:05:02,158 --> 00:05:04,672
He jumped into it as soon as we took it out of the crate.

83
00:05:04,746 --> 00:05:06,182
Slept in it that night.

84
00:05:06,638 --> 00:05:08,741
And every night until...

85
00:05:12,806 --> 00:05:14,783
Kyle, is there anything else you want to ask?

86
00:05:14,788 --> 00:05:16,670
Yes. Who's Adam Bailen?

87
00:05:18,068 --> 00:05:20,820
-Doesn't sound familiar.
-What about Professor William Kern?

88
00:05:20,826 --> 00:05:21,590
Who?

89
00:05:21,907 --> 00:05:23,811
This logo, do you recognize it?

90
00:05:23,825 --> 00:05:26,190
-Kyle.
-No, they act like they know me.

91
00:05:26,577 --> 00:05:28,761
They can't tell me anything to help me remember.

92
00:05:28,807 --> 00:05:32,602
And they don't know why people are missing or dead or how these people are connected to me.

93
00:05:33,335 --> 00:05:35,001
It's a lot to take in.

94
00:05:35,556 --> 00:05:39,583
Seems like for all of you,
five years is just...gone.

95
00:05:46,628 --> 00:05:48,963
Let's go, people. God is waiting.

96
00:05:50,225 --> 00:05:52,623
You want to go to Amanda's confirmation with me?

97
00:05:52,728 --> 00:05:53,933
Sure!

98
00:05:54,148 --> 00:05:57,803
Church  is neat, and I never get a chance to wear this suit.

99
00:05:57,885 --> 00:05:59,403
When do you ever wear that suit?

100
00:06:00,497 --> 00:06:02,883
And when did you start reeking of my aftershave?

101
00:06:03,105 --> 00:06:05,141
Ah! What's her name?

102
00:06:05,326 --> 00:06:09,591
Okay, maybe there's this girl named Ashley that I met at a party.

103
00:06:09,675 --> 00:06:12,703
Maybe she goes to Holy Family and sings in the choir.

104
00:06:12,717 --> 00:06:17,283
And maybe she finds the scent of a man irresistible.

105
00:06:17,948 --> 00:06:20,850
Hey, tuck in your shirt.
The Lord hates a slob.

106
00:06:20,978 --> 00:06:23,492
Watch yourself, Josh.
Church isn't supposed to be fun.

107
00:06:23,696 --> 00:06:25,522
Oh, is that why you never go?

108
00:06:36,807 --> 00:06:38,603
God, she's hot.

109
00:06:39,117 --> 00:06:44,790
Oh, my God, can I even say "God"? Sorry.

110
00:06:52,168 --> 00:06:55,972
<i>Everywhere I looked, 
church provided unsettling contrasts.</i>

111
00:06:58,188 --> 00:07:02,160
<i>People whose beliefs encouraged honesty also practiced betrayal.</i>

112
00:07:03,898 --> 00:07:06,610
<i>There  was a lot about church I didn't understand.</i>

113
00:07:06,656 --> 00:07:11,583
<i>But I did know that faith meant believing in something, often without tangible proof.</i>

114
00:07:11,588 --> 00:07:14,782
<i>I wondered if I'd be able to do the same with the Petersons.</i>

115
00:07:14,915 --> 00:07:17,301
<i>And come to accept them whole-heartedly.</i>

116
00:07:17,907 --> 00:07:19,743
What's he putting on her head?

117
00:07:21,006 --> 00:07:23,473
Everyone else is being quiet, Josh.

118
00:07:23,485 --> 00:07:25,833
I think we should be quiet, too.

119
00:07:31,987 --> 00:07:34,443
Church walls crumble at the sight of you?

120
00:07:35,688 --> 00:07:37,113
Very funny.

121
00:07:40,535 --> 00:07:43,280
I had gotten used to Kyle having no memories.

122
00:07:45,108 --> 00:07:49,003
It feels kind of strange to have his whole life laid out before us.

123
00:07:49,165 --> 00:07:52,002
Well, he looks happy in these photos.

124
00:07:52,807 --> 00:07:54,783
-How are you doing?
-I'm fine.

125
00:07:57,107 --> 00:07:59,081
You can't be fine. I'm not fine.

126
00:07:59,758 --> 00:08:04,032
Look, since day one he's been searching for clues to who he is and where he comes from...

127
00:08:05,047 --> 00:08:06,820
And now he knows.

128
00:08:07,155 --> 00:08:09,833
For me to be upset would just be selfish.

129
00:08:10,535 --> 00:08:12,150
Or human.

130
00:08:16,288 --> 00:08:17,513
I'm fine.

131
00:08:31,336 --> 00:08:34,222
I'm just so proud of her.

132
00:08:37,676 --> 00:08:42,012
Oh. Look, it's our neighbor.

133
00:08:42,015 --> 00:08:43,833
-Hi.
-Hi.

134
00:08:44,048 --> 00:08:46,202
Hey, Kyle. Good to see you feeling better.

135
00:08:48,548 --> 00:08:49,623
Thanks.

136
00:08:50,687 --> 00:08:53,403
Amanda, I think we should go and thank the Bishop now, okay?

137
00:08:53,408 --> 00:08:55,860
-We  already thanked him.
-Amanda...

138
00:08:59,018 --> 00:09:00,742
-Okay. God.
-Shh!

139
00:09:03,455 --> 00:09:05,273
Her mother's a piece of work.

140
00:09:06,016 --> 00:09:08,682
I think Amanda has bigger problems right now.

141
00:09:09,748 --> 00:09:11,491
I know about Hillary.

142
00:09:14,885 --> 00:09:16,313
You can't tell her.

143
00:09:17,295 --> 00:09:19,390
I'm not the one who should.

144
00:09:21,321 --> 00:09:24,982
-Men are such dogs.
-Gee, thanks.

145
00:09:26,406 --> 00:09:28,853
You've proven yourself to be moderately un-doglike.

146
00:09:28,858 --> 00:09:31,971
But Amanda's the nicest girl in the universe.

147
00:09:31,995 --> 00:09:33,743
How could he cheat on her?

148
00:09:34,075 --> 00:09:37,883
She's a nice girl who doesn't believe in sex before marriage, and he's a guy.

149
00:09:38,796 --> 00:09:40,430
That's hideous logic.

150
00:09:40,466 --> 00:09:41,803
But accurate.

151
00:09:42,126 --> 00:09:45,021
-Church sucks.
-News flash.

152
00:09:45,155 --> 00:09:46,871
Did you get the DNA results?

153
00:09:47,486 --> 00:09:48,512
Not yet.

154
00:09:48,585 --> 00:09:50,473
Did the police run their plates?

155
00:09:50,666 --> 00:09:53,510
Have they done anything to prove the Petersons are who they say they are?

156
00:09:53,608 --> 00:09:55,040
They're not criminals, Declan.

157
00:09:55,047 --> 00:09:58,551
They're a nice married couple from Connecticut who lost their son.

158
00:10:02,395 --> 00:10:04,973
-I just want to make sure.
-He has a point.

159
00:10:05,615 --> 00:10:10,963
I mean, aliens can't just land their craft on the front yard and retrieve Kyle without drawing attention.

160
00:10:10,965 --> 00:10:13,101
They've hatched the perfect plan.

161
00:10:13,178 --> 00:10:16,601
We invite them into our home and they make off with our alien.

162
00:10:20,396 --> 00:10:21,400
What?

163
00:10:27,148 --> 00:10:28,903
You wanted to see me, Miss Thatcher?

164
00:10:29,065 --> 00:10:35,522
Every day that subject 781227 remains alive
we risk someone discovering his abilities.

165
00:10:35,526 --> 00:10:37,302
He's surrounded by people all the time.

166
00:10:37,375 --> 00:10:39,943
It makes it very complicated to try to take him out.

167
00:10:40,286 --> 00:10:41,912
But I do have a plan in motion.

168
00:10:41,918 --> 00:10:45,720
Just find a moment when he's alone and get rid of him.

169
00:10:47,376 --> 00:10:53,191
I do not want any evidence of our experiment to exist outside the walls of this company.

170
00:10:59,216 --> 00:11:00,920
All right, we'll think this through.

171
00:11:01,215 --> 00:11:03,533
You remember being in the back of a car on a raining night?

172
00:11:03,548 --> 00:11:06,183
I've seen Tomm Foss killed Professor Kern in the woods.

173
00:11:06,358 --> 00:11:07,912
And then you woke up alone.

174
00:11:07,937 --> 00:11:09,972
But no memory of what just happened.

175
00:11:10,305 --> 00:11:11,951
No memories at all.

176
00:11:13,995 --> 00:11:16,662
But we know Prefessor Kern was connected to Adam Bailen.

177
00:11:16,688 --> 00:11:19,741
Who looked just like me 20 years ago before he disappeared.

178
00:11:20,746 --> 00:11:23,593
I'm also ruling out time-travel and aliens and pink goo.

179
00:11:23,978 --> 00:11:25,550
It's too ridiculous.

180
00:11:26,808 --> 00:11:29,613
And Adam Bailen drew a picture of the key card logo.

181
00:11:29,738 --> 00:11:31,303
Which you subconsciously drew.

182
00:11:31,348 --> 00:11:34,472
Which led me to the coordinates of a location I couldn't identify.

183
00:11:34,617 --> 00:11:36,713
And then your suppossed real parents showed up.

184
00:11:36,717 --> 00:11:39,393
With no idea where I've been for the past five years.

185
00:11:39,716 --> 00:11:41,961
Or why I can do the things I can do.

186
00:11:43,735 --> 00:11:45,171
I got nothing.

187
00:11:47,868 --> 00:11:50,342
But you're not a superhero either.

188
00:11:51,888 --> 00:11:53,680
I wish more things would come back to me.

189
00:11:53,777 --> 00:11:55,270
They're trapped in my head.

190
00:11:55,927 --> 00:11:57,972
I bet Tom Foss could put those pieces together.

191
00:11:57,975 --> 00:12:01,341
We can't go near Foss. It's too dangerous.

192
00:12:04,906 --> 00:12:08,321
You should have seen Charlie all clean-cut and churchy.

193
00:12:08,408 --> 00:12:11,282
Holding her hand like a frickin' choir boy.

194
00:12:12,477 --> 00:12:15,350
Too bad she can't make him sing like I can.

195
00:12:15,485 --> 00:12:19,792
Hill, I hate to be all doom and gloomy,
but you know this can't end well, right?

196
00:12:20,676 --> 00:12:24,052
I know he doesn't want to hurt her right now
because she lost her dad and everything.

197
00:12:24,278 --> 00:12:25,213
But I can wait.

198
00:12:25,428 --> 00:12:27,612
And what happens if he dumps her for you?

199
00:12:27,767 --> 00:12:30,431
You're with a guy who is cheating on his girlfriend.

200
00:12:30,448 --> 00:12:32,800
What's to say he won't do the same thing to you?

201
00:12:32,955 --> 00:12:35,351
How are you suddenly a relationship expert?

202
00:12:35,355 --> 00:12:37,831
It's not like Declan's Mr.Ideal boyfriend.

203
00:12:38,177 --> 00:12:43,443
No, but weirdly enough, I trust him.

204
00:12:44,545 --> 00:12:47,532
-Turnaround of the century.
-Crazy, huh?

205
00:12:49,025 --> 00:12:50,611
But sweet.

206
00:12:53,065 --> 00:12:55,082
I'm happy for you.

207
00:12:56,808 --> 00:12:59,393
I didn't get a chance to thank you for my present.

208
00:12:59,955 --> 00:13:01,343
It was really thoughtful.

209
00:13:01,718 --> 00:13:05,090
-St. Colette is--
-The patron saint of people who have lost a parent.

210
00:13:06,916 --> 00:13:08,090
Yeah.

211
00:13:11,245 --> 00:13:15,141
We still haven't had the chance to talk about everything that's happened to you since yesterday.

212
00:13:19,545 --> 00:13:20,703
You want to?

213
00:13:33,326 --> 00:13:34,732
You should be happy.

214
00:13:35,956 --> 00:13:37,343
You don't look happy.

215
00:13:39,627 --> 00:13:40,811
I'm not.

216
00:13:42,606 --> 00:13:44,750
You know it's a funny thing about my religion.

217
00:13:44,868 --> 00:13:49,361
There's a saint for pretty much everything--
cab drivers, stomach aches, geese.

218
00:13:49,645 --> 00:13:52,163
There's even a patron saint for bald people.

219
00:13:52,858 --> 00:13:55,392
Sometimes  I wonder if everything is covered.

220
00:13:56,146 --> 00:13:58,990
Then why do so many bad things happen to people?

221
00:14:00,846 --> 00:14:04,943
Then I realized that everyone needs something to get us through the bad stuff.

222
00:14:06,188 --> 00:14:08,011
So I need a saint.

223
00:14:10,186 --> 00:14:13,693
The patron saint of lost paths and confusing futures.

224
00:14:16,035 --> 00:14:18,581
Any idea where I can find one?

225
00:14:22,365 --> 00:14:24,021
Why do they have to come over again?

226
00:14:24,026 --> 00:14:26,100
Well, nothing's triggered any recognition yet.

227
00:14:26,105 --> 00:14:29,583
So the more they get to know each other, the more hope we have of Kyle remembering them.

228
00:14:29,585 --> 00:14:31,392
Unless there's nothing to remember.

229
00:14:32,338 --> 00:14:35,750
Josh has spun an alien conspira theory of epic proportions.

230
00:14:35,775 --> 00:14:37,442
Okay, I understand this is difficult.

231
00:14:37,447 --> 00:14:40,773
But we have to start dealing with the idea that Kyle might be leaving us.

232
00:14:44,738 --> 00:14:46,141
What's the matter?

233
00:14:46,615 --> 00:14:48,832
I just got off the phone with the hospital.

234
00:14:50,057 --> 00:14:51,962
The DNA is a match.

235
00:14:56,687 --> 00:14:59,012
Well, now we know.

236
00:15:03,905 --> 00:15:05,681
I'm not going with them.

237
00:15:07,116 --> 00:15:08,423
Damn straight.

238
00:15:08,967 --> 00:15:10,600
Kyle...

239
00:15:10,688 --> 00:15:14,232
Of course we don't want to lose you,
but it's not that easy.

240
00:15:14,688 --> 00:15:16,512
They're your family.

241
00:15:19,356 --> 00:15:21,152
You're my family.

242
00:15:23,216 --> 00:15:26,260
I don't care what the test says.
They're strangers to me.

243
00:15:28,096 --> 00:15:31,512
How can I go live with them when you're the only family I know?

244
00:15:44,205 --> 00:15:46,360
-Kyle, wait.
-Honey...

245
00:15:56,026 --> 00:16:00,950
<i>I had read the story of the father who sacrificed his son for the good of all of mankind.</i>

246
00:16:01,275 --> 00:16:06,673
<i>I wondered if having faith meant making our own sacrifices for the good of others.</i>

247
00:16:22,147 --> 00:16:24,012
You can kneel if you want to.

248
00:16:24,095 --> 00:16:28,253
It helps sometimes,
gets you in the mood to pray.

249
00:16:31,595 --> 00:16:33,740
I've never prayed before.

250
00:16:34,217 --> 00:16:35,771
It's simple.

251
00:16:35,985 --> 00:16:38,791
It's like telling your troubles to a friendly ear.

252
00:16:43,605 --> 00:16:45,600
I'm in search of a saint.

253
00:16:46,488 --> 00:16:48,361
You picked a good place.

254
00:16:51,507 --> 00:16:53,603
What do you need a saint for?

255
00:16:57,976 --> 00:17:00,162
I don't know where I belong.

256
00:17:00,855 --> 00:17:03,193
I don't know where I come from...

257
00:17:04,777 --> 00:17:07,990
